Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction Habituation, the mechanism by which the brain learns to ignore repeated stimuli, is the most basic form of plasticity within the brain. It has been investigated thoroughly in recent years by biologists in a number of different animals, from the sea snail Aplysia <ref> [1, 2, 3, 5] </ref> through to cats [11] and toads [4, 14]. Of itself, habituation is an interesting phenomenon and therefore worthy of investigation, but there are several worthwhile uses to which it can be put. <p> This demonstrates that habituation is a two stage process, there is a short-term effect lasting for a few minutes and a long-term effect lasting for hours. For a more comprehensive review, see <ref> [1, 19] </ref>. Although habituation causes a decrement in response, the full response can be regained without allowing the animal to rest, for example by training with a different stimulus. This makes it different to fatigue. For a complete definition of habituation, see Thompson and Spencer [12].
